# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emiew
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] 1X Technologies was founded in 2014 by Norwegian roboticist Bernt Øivind Børnich under the name Halodi Robotics.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] The company initially focused on developing safe actuators and full-body control systems for industrial and healthcare robotics.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] In 2018, it released its first humanoid robot, EVE, designed for logistics, security, and medical environments.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] In 2022, the company rebranded as 1X Technologies and shifted its focus to domestic robotics, developing humanoid assistants intended for use in private homes.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] In March 2023, 1X raised $23.5 million in Series A2 funding, led by the OpenAI Startup Fund, with participation from Tiger Global, Sandwater, Alliance Ventures, and Skagerak Capital.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] In January 2024, the company secured $100 million in Series B funding led by EQT Ventures, alongside Samsung NEXT, Nistad Group, and existing investors.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] In September 2025, it was reported that 1X Technologies was seeking to raise $1 billion in new funding to support the development and deployment of its humanoid robots for home environments.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] On October 28, 2025, 1X opened pre-orders for NEO, also known as NEO Home Robot, a humanoid robot designed for use in private homes, scheduled for release in 2026.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] It will be available in tan, gray, and dark brown, and cost $20,000 for early adopters; it is also planned to be offered as a subscription service for $499 per month.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] Joanna Stern reported that as of October 2025, most tasks were teleoperated by a human with a virtual reality headset, raising concerns about privacy.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] The company plans to provide an app where users can schedule sessions during which a remote operator can accomplish tasks.
[src:emiew/1x-technologies] CEO Bernt Børnich said that obtaining training data from early adopters was needed to improve the autonomy of the robot.
[src:emiew/agibot] In December 2024, AgiBot said it had begun mass production.
[src:emiew/agibot] According to media reports, the firm stated it had produced 962 units as of December 15, 2024.
[src:emiew/agibot] In November 2025, the AgiBot A2 robot was recognized by Guinness World Records for walking a distance of 106.286 kilometers.
[src:emiew/agibot] In August 2023, AgiBot launched its first humanoid robot, RAISE A1 aimed at industrial applications doing tasks such as tasks like bolt tightening, vehicle inspections, and laboratory experiments.
[src:emiew/agibot] It is equipped with RGBD camera, Lidar sensors, and modular components to handle various scenarios.
[src:emiew/agibot] RAISE A1 stands at 1.75 meters tall, weighs 53 kilograms and has 49 degrees of freedom. it is capable of walking at speeds up to 7 km/h and handle loads up to 80 kilograms.
[src:emiew/agibot] There are plans to expand RAISE A1's duties to perform household chores.
[src:emiew/agibot] The second model listed on Agibot's website is the cleaning robot C5 which is designed to perform sweeping, scrubbing, and dust mopping together.
[src:emiew/agibot] It is equipped with functions such as automatic charging, automatic water filling and drainage, and self-cleaning of the sewage tank.
[src:emiew/agibot] In August 2024, AgiBot introduced five new models of robots designed for various applications.
[src:emiew/agibot] They were three Yuanzheng models (A2, A2-Max and A2-W) and two Lingxi models (X1 and X1-W) At the center of the five robots shown was the Yuanzheng A2, a biped humanoid robot with a height of 1.75 meters and weighs 55 kilograms.
[src:emiew/agibot] Built with various sensors and powered by AI it can see, hear and process information obtained.
[src:emiew/agibot] It was designed to perform tasks as delicate as inserting a thread through the eye of a needle.
[src:emiew/agibot] Another bipedal model Lingxi X1 would be open source and AgiBot would later publish most design material and codes to help more developers.
[src:emiew/agibot] Media reports compared them with Tesla's Optimus.
[src:emiew/agibot] AgiBot also introduced AIDEA, a comprehensive embodied AI data system for collecting and processing robot interaction data.
[src:emiew/agibot] AgiBot exhibited its robots at the 2024 World Robot Conference in Beijing.
[src:emiew/agibot] At the end of 2024, AgiBot said it plans to allow public access to its robot database AgiBot World to achieve unified standards and reduce the unnecessary duplication of tasks during development.
[src:emiew/agibot] It claimed AgiBot World to be larger and of higher quality than Google's Open X-Embodiment which is the open source equivalent.
[src:emiew/agibot] According to *Reuters*, Shanghai authorities supported the establishment of an AgiBot data‑collection site where hundreds of robots are tele‑operated to generate training data for embodied‑AI models.
[src:emiew/agibot] The company also operates a factory in Shanghai that it said entered mass‑production preparation in 2024.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:emiew/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:emiew/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In 2019, Ai-Da was conceived by gallerist Aidan Meller as an AI art generator embodied as a life-like humanoid robot.
[src:emiew/ai-da] The hardware was built in collaboration with Engineered Arts, a Cornish robotics company.
[src:emiew/ai-da] The graphics algorithms allowing it to draw were developed by computer AI researchers at the University of Oxford, and its drawing arm was developed by Salaheldin Al Abd and Ziad Abass, students from the School of Electronic and Electrical Engineering at the University of Leeds.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In April 2022, Ai-Da was equipped with a new arm that enabled it to paint using a palette, first shown at the British Library in London.
[src:emiew/ai-da] Aidan Meller presented artworks from Ai-Da at a solo show called *Ai-Da: Portrait of a Robot* at the Design Museum in London, including "self-portraits", an apparent paradox given a robot has no "self".
[src:emiew/ai-da] This raised questions about identity in the digital age, and the effects artificial intelligence may have on art in the future.
[src:emiew/ai-da] It was also the first humanoid to devise a font, displayed at the Design Museum.
[src:emiew/ai-da] Algorithms for collaborative sculpture were added to Ai-Da's capabilities in 2022.
[src:emiew/ai-da] Ai-Da can be displayed in either a standing or seated position; although it has legs, it cannot walk.
[src:emiew/ai-da] A pair of cameras in the robot's eyes allow the robot to both make eye contact and, in conjunction with a computer vision algorithm and a modified robotic arm, create sketches of the robot's surroundings.
[src:emiew/ai-da] Ai-Da has been exhibited alongside sculptures, however the robot's involvement in sculpture creation is minimal: pencil sketches created by Ai-Da are turned into sculptures by an uncredited artist, then 3D printed and cast in bronze.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In addition to art generation, Ai-Da can allegedly use "speech pattern analysis, plus an internal data bank of words" to generate poetry, as well as respond to questions using a language model.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In May 2019, Ai-Da executed a live performance called *Privacy* at St Hugh's College, Oxford.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In June 2019, art generated by Ai-Da was featured in a gallery show called *Unsecured Futures* at St John's College, University of Oxford.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In June 2019, Ai-Da featured at the Barbican Centre, London, in WIRED Pulse: AI.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In September 2019, the Ars Electronica, Linz, Austria: European ARTificial Intelligence Lab exhibition entitled *Out of the Box: The Midlife Crisis of the Digital Revolution* invited a performance from Ai-Da.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In October 2019, the artist Sadie Clayton worked with Ai-Da on a series of workshops at Tate Exchange, Tate Modern, London – *Exploring Identity Through Technology* – hosted by *A Vibe Called Tech*.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In November, 2019, Ai-Da was displayed at Abu Dhabi Art in Manarat Al Saadiyat, UAE.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In December 2019, Ai-Da had her first "interview" with Tim Marlow, the artistic director at the Royal Academy, at the Sarabande (Alexander McQueen Foundation), London, Inspiration Series.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In July 2020, Ai-Da featured in The 1975's music video for their song "Yeah I Know", from their album *Notes on a Conditional Form*.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In the video, Ai-Da appears drawing a representation of human consciousness and generating a poem in response to the song's lyrics.
[src:emiew/ai-da] The album went to No.1 in the USA charts.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In May 2021, Ai-Da was installed at Porthmeor Studios, St Ives.
[src:emiew/ai-da] Located in Studio 5, Ai-Da generated art in response to the work of Ben Nicholson's, who worked in the same space during the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In May 2021, "self-portraits" of Ai-Da were displayed in *Ai-Da: Portrait of the Robot* at the Design Museum, London.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In September 2021, Ai-Da exhibited her first Metaverse works at the Victoria and Albert Museum during the London Design Festival.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In October 2021, while entering Egypt for an exhibition at the Great Pyramid of Giza, Ai-Da was held for ten days by border guards who "feared her robotics may have been hiding covert spy tools".
[src:emiew/ai-da] The artwork was part of the contemporary art exhibition to be held for the first time at the Pyramids in 4500 years.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In October 2021, artworks and poetry generated by Ai-Da were featured as part of a group show called "Dante: the invention of Celebrity" at the Ashmolean Museum, Oxford.
[src:emiew/ai-da] On 22 April 2022, an exhibition titled "Leaping into the Metaverse" featuring Ai-Da launched during the 59th Venice Biennale.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In May 2022, *Algorithm Queen*, a painting generated by Ai-Da which depicts Queen Elizabeth II, was unveiled to mark her platinum jubilee.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In June 2022, Ai-Da was invited to be an "artist in residence" at Glastonbury Festival, in the ShangriLa Field, along with Chinese dissident artist Ai WeiWei.
[src:emiew/ai-da] Ai-Da painted the headliners Billie Eilish, Kendrick Lamar, Sir Paul McCartney, and Diana Ross while interacting with the crowds in her studio.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In September 2022, Ai-Da was featured in an exhibition called "*Imagining AI"* by the Bodleian Library, University of Oxford, the Cheney School, the Rumble Museum, Open Doors and the University of Oxford Maths Department.
[src:emiew/ai-da] The series highlighted the ever-changing and rapid growth of artificial intelligence.
[src:emiew/ai-da] Attendees could see Ai-Da in a "live" Q&A and art session.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In October 2022 Ai-Da was shown at The Louvre Abu Dhabi, and later was used to present a Keynote Talk at The Cultural Summit, Abu Dhabi with Tim Marlow, chief executive and director of the Design Museum in London, which is organised by the Abu Dhabi Department of Culture and Tourism.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In October 2022, Ai-Da became the first humanoid robot to give evidence at the House of Lords, Palace of Westminster, as part of its *A Creative Future* inquiry, examining potential challenges for the creative industries and looking at how they can adapt as technology advances.
[src:emiew/ai-da] During the session, the robot inadvertently shut down and needed to be restarted.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In November 2022, Ai-Da became the first robot to speak at the Oxford Union debating society.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In November 2022, Ai-Da was featured as a "guest of honour speaker" at the Wadi Ashar Dialogue in AlUla, Saudi Arabia.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In April 2023, Ai-Da created the world’s largest participatory AI artwork, at an exhibition called *Saw This Made This*, at the Chelsea Arts Factory, New York, and Design Museum, London.
[src:emiew/ai-da] Ai-Da was interviewed by Baz Luhrmann and Tim Marlow as part of the exhibition.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In June 2023, Ai-Da made history as the first humanoid robot to design, displaying homewares in her pavilion called *AI Mind Home* at Somerset House, London, as part of the London Design Biennale.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In June 2023, Ai-Da made history as the first humanoid robot to speak at No.10 Downing Street to the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, and Media, the Rt Hon Lucy Frazer KC MP.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In July 2023, at United Nations, Geneva, AI for Good Global Summit, Ai-Da gave a keynote speech and performed Dawn Mizzle, and had an art exhibition.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In December, 2023, Ai-Da painted a live portrait of Professor Michael Wooldridge at the Royal Institution Christmas Lectures, the Head of Computer Science, University of Oxford, and Director for AI at The Alan Turing Institute, London.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In July 2024, Ai-Da exhibited a Polyptych of Alan Turing, Ada Lovelace and a Self Portrait at the United Nations, Geneva at the AI for Good Global Summit, and gave a keynote speech.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In November 2024, Ai-Da made history, by selling “AI God: Portrait of Alan Turing”, right hand panel of a large scale triptych, at Sotheby’s New York for US$1.1Million, breaking all records for art made by a humanoid robot.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In July 2025, Ai-Da unveiled a portrait of King Charles III at the UK Home Mission, Geneva, and later at the United Nations at the AI for Good Global Summit in Geneva.
[src:emiew/ai-da] At the same event Ai-Da also met His Excellency Mr Alar Karis, President of Estonia, to sit for his portrait.
[src:emiew/ai-da] In January 2026, Ai-Da made history as the first humanoid robot to do concept art called Ai-Da: Space Pod, designs for a building as part of a modular structure as habitation for Moon or Mars.
[src:emiew/ai-da] The timing of the exhibition was to tie in with NASA's Artemis II Moon Program, taking place at the same time.
[src:emiew/ai-da] Ai-Da presented the works at an exhibition called *I am not a robot*, at the Utzon Center in Aalborg, Denmark.
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:emiew/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] Alpha was among several notable humanoid robots demonstrated during the interwar period, following earlier machines such as Eric.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] The robot became known for its public demonstrations, including responding to voice commands, moving its arms and head, answering prepared questions, and firing a revolver as part of stage performances.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] Alpha was developed by British inventor Harry May during the early 1930s.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] The robot was constructed with a chromium-plated steel exterior and stood approximately 6 feet 4 inches (1.93 m) tall.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] Contemporary reports described Alpha as being capable of standing, sitting, turning its head, raising its arms, and replying to spoken questions.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] The robot first gained attention at the 1932 London Radio Exhibition at Olympia, where it appeared on the Mullard stand promoting thermionic valve technology.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] The demonstrations were largely theatrical and involved concealed operators and prerecorded responses.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] May later toured with Alpha internationally, including exhibitions in Canada and the United States.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] Alpha became the subject of sensational newspaper coverage in 1932 after reports claimed that the robot had shot and injured Harry May during a demonstration in Brighton, England.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] According to widely circulated accounts, Alpha unexpectedly rose from its chair and fired a revolver before May had issued the intended command.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] Later research suggested that many details of the incident were exaggerated by newspapers and that the injury may instead have resulted from an accidental discharge while the weapon was being loaded.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] The story became an early example of public anxiety surrounding automation and humanoid machines during the Great Depression era.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] Alpha is regarded as one of the notable humanoid exhibition robots of the early twentieth century.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] Historians of technology have cited the machine as an example of how robots were presented as both entertainment and symbols of technological progress during the interwar years.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] Photographs and footage of Alpha have continued to circulate in retrospectives on early robotics and retrofuturism.
[src:emiew/alpha-robot] A demonstration video of Alpha with its inventor survives and has been published on YouTube under the title ''*Alpha The Robot (1934)*''.
[src:emiew/asimo] E0 was the first bipedal model produced as part of the Honda E series, which was an early experimental line of self-regulating walking robots with wireless movements created between 1986 and 1993.
[src:emiew/asimo] This was followed by the Honda P series of robots produced from 1993 through 1997.
[src:emiew/asimo] The research made on the E- and P-series led to the creation of ASIMO.
[src:emiew/asimo] Development began at Honda's Wako Fundamental Technical Research Center in Japan in 1999, and ASIMO was unveiled in October 2000.
[src:emiew/asimo] In 2002, 20 units of the first model were produced.
[src:emiew/asimo] In July 2018, Honda stated that it would be ceasing all development and production of ASIMO robots in order to focus on more practical applications using the technology developed through ASIMO's lifespan.
[src:emiew/asimo] It made its last active appearance in March 2022, as Honda announced the retirement of ASIMO to concentrate on remote-controlled, avatar-style robotic technology.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO stands 130 cm (4 ft 3 in) tall and weighs 54 kg (119 lb).
[src:emiew/asimo] Research conducted by Honda found that the ideal height for a mobility assistant robot was between 120 cm and the height of an average adult, which is conducive to operating door knobs and light switches.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO is powered by a rechargeable 51.8 V lithium-ion battery with an operating time of one hour.
[src:emiew/asimo] Switching from a nickel–metal hydride battery in 2004 increased the amount of time ASIMO can operate before recharging.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO has a three-dimensional computer processor created by Honda that consists of three stacked dies, a processor, a signal converter, and memory.
[src:emiew/asimo] The computer that controls ASIMO's movement is housed in the robot's waist area and can be controlled using a PC, wireless controller, or voice commands.
[src:emiew/asimo] Using visual information captured by two camera "eyes", ASIMO has the ability to recognize moving objects (and determine their distance and direction), postures, gestures, its surrounding environment, sounds, and faces.
[src:emiew/asimo] Some of these features enable ASIMO to interact with humans, including by facing a person when approached or following them.
[src:emiew/asimo] The robot interprets voice commands and gestures, e.g. enabling it to respond accordingly when a handshake is offered or when a person waves or points.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO's ability to distinguish between voices and other sounds allows it to identify its companions.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO is able to respond to its name and recognizes sounds associated with a falling object or collision.
[src:emiew/asimo] This allows the robot to face a person when spoken to or look towards a sound.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO responds to questions by nodding or providing a verbal answer in different languages and can recognize approximately 10 different faces and address them by name.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO is equipped with sensors that assist in autonomous navigation.
[src:emiew/asimo] The two cameras inside its head act as visual sensors to detect obstacles.
[src:emiew/asimo] The lower portion of the torso has two ground sensors—one laser sensor and one infrared sensor.
[src:emiew/asimo] The laser sensor is used to detect the ground surface, and the infrared sensor with automatic shutter adjustment based on brightness is used to detect pairs of floor markings to navigate along paths.
[src:emiew/asimo] A pre-loaded map and the detection of floor markings help the robot to precisely identify its present location and continuously adjust its position.
[src:emiew/asimo] There are front and rear ultrasonic sensors to sense obstacles; the front sensor is located at the lower torso together with the ground sensors, and the rear sensor is located at the bottom of the "backpack".
[src:emiew/asimo] Honda's work with ASIMO led to further research on walking assist devices, resulting in the Stride Management Assist and Bodyweight Support Assist prototypes.
[src:emiew/asimo] In 2004, ASIMO was inducted into the Carnegie Mellon Robot Hall of Fame.
[src:emiew/asimo] In honor of ASIMO's 10th anniversary in November 2010, Honda developed a mobile app called "Run with ASIMO", wherein users learn about the robot by virtually walking it through the steps of a race and then sharing their lap times on Twitter and Facebook.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO was also the inspiration behind the 2012 film *Robot & Frank*, wherein a similar humanoid robot, portrayed by an actress in a costume, assists an aging cat burglar.
[src:emiew/asimo] Since ASIMO was introduced in 2000, the robot has traveled around the world and performed in front of international audiences.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO made its first public appearance in the United States in 2002 when it rang the bell to open trade sessions for the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:emiew/asimo] The robot first visited the United Kingdom in January 2003 for private demonstrations at the Science Museum in London.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO continued on a world tour, making stops in countries such as Spain, the United Arab Emirates, Russia, South Africa, and Australia.
[src:emiew/asimo] From January 2003 to March 2005, the robot toured the US and Canada, demonstrating its abilities for more than 130,000 people.
[src:emiew/asimo] From 2003 to 2004, ASIMO was part of a North American educational tour, where it visited top science and technology museums and academic institutions throughout North America.
[src:emiew/asimo] The goal of the tour was to encourage students to study science through a live show that highlighted ASIMO's abilities.
[src:emiew/asimo] Additionally, the robot visited top engineering and computer science colleges and universities across the US as part of the ASIMO Technology Circuit Tour in an effort to encourage students to consider scientific careers.
[src:emiew/asimo] In March 2005, ASIMO walked the red carpet at the world premiere of the animated film *Robots*.
[src:emiew/asimo] In June of that year, the robot became a feature in a show called "Say 'Hello' to Honda's ASIMO" at Disneyland's Innoventions attraction, which was a part of the Tomorrowland area of the park.
[src:emiew/asimo] This was the only permanent installation of ASIMO in North America until Innoventions was closed in April 2015.
[src:emiew/asimo] In a demonstration at Honda's Tokyo headquarters in 2007, the company demonstrated new intelligence technologies that enabled multiple ASIMO robots to work together.
[src:emiew/asimo] The demonstration showed the robot's ability to identify and avoid oncoming people, work with another ASIMO, recognize when to recharge its battery, and perform new tasks such as carrying a tray and pushing a cart.
[src:emiew/asimo] In October 2008, ASIMO greeted Prince Charles during a visit to the Miraikan museum in Tokyo, where it performed a seven-minute step and dance routine.
[src:emiew/asimo] In 2014, then–US President Barack Obama was introduced to ASIMO at Miraikan.
[src:emiew/asimo] In 2008, ASIMO conducted the Detroit Symphony Orchestra in a performance of "The Impossible Dream" to bring attention to its partnership with the orchestra and support performing arts in Detroit.
[src:emiew/asimo] A 49-foot replica of ASIMO made with natural materials, such as lettuce seed, rice and carnations, led the 120th Rose Parade in celebration of Honda's 50th year of operation in the US.
[src:emiew/asimo] Later that year, the robot made an appearance at the Genoa Science Festival in Italy.
[src:emiew/asimo] In January 2010, Honda debuted a 10-minute documentary at the Sundance Film Festival that focuses on the experience of human interaction with robots like ASIMO.
[src:emiew/asimo] The robot attended the Ars Electronica festival in Linz, Austria, in September 2010, which allowed Honda to study the results of human–robot interaction and use the results to guide development of future versions of the robot.
[src:emiew/asimo] In April 2011, ASIMO was demonstrated at the FIRST Championship in St.
[src:emiew/asimo] Louis, Missouri, to encourage students to pursue studies in math, science and engineering.
[src:emiew/asimo] That November, ASIMO was one of the star attractions at the first Abu Dhabi Science Festival.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO visited the Ontario Science Center in Toronto in May 2011 and demonstrated its abilities to Canadian students.
[src:emiew/asimo] The robot later traveled to Ottawa for the unveiling of an exhibit at the Canadian Museum of Civilization 19 May through 22 May 2011.
[src:emiew/asimo] ASIMO appeared as a guest on the British quiz show *QI* on 2 December 2011.
[src:emiew/asimo] After serving water to host Stephen Fry and dancing with comedian Jo Brand, ASIMO won with 32 points.
[src:emiew/asimo] On 24 March 2017, Honda revealed ASIMO in Disneyland's Autopia attraction.
[src:emiew/asimo] On multiple occasions, audience members at public showcasings of ASIMO have filmed the robot malfunctioning and falling down stairs.
[src:emiew/asimo] These videos have been uploaded on YouTube, and some have become viral for their comedic nature.
